The 1965 Immigration Act and subsequent acts greatly reduced border restrictions, leading to an exponential surge in unpermitted migration from Central and South American nations.

The statement was not correct. Other former Anglo colonies, as well as French, Spanish, and Portuguese colonies had extensive racial classification systems. During the slave rebellion era in Haiti, plantation owners called for anyone with even 'one drop' of black blood to be executed. https://msu.edu/~williss2/carpentier/part2/quadroons.html French Caribbean colonies had designations for every combination of black ancestry, up to even 1/64th black.

/* 16th and 17th centuries */Factually incorrect – Spanish inhabitants abandoned Florida after it was acquired by the British, with the only Spanish contacts being traveling merchants to former port cities such as St. Augustine, and later Spanish immigrants from Spain after the territory came under American control. Spanish presence in Florida did not resurge until the middle of the twentieth century.

Factually incorrect – St. Augustine was not continuously inhabited by a Spanish population. It was abandoned by the Spanish after Florida came under British control, visited only by Spanish merchants for the following centuries. Spanish presence in Florida resurged in the middle of the 20th century. But, even if it were continuously inhabited by the Spanish, there was never a Spanish presence within the colonial United States, in contradiction to the author's claim.
/* Demographics */Incorrect statistics, and included unrelated information.
